{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_irma_ver01/data/sn88078614/00516994071/1948082701/0547.xml":{"full_text":"ATTEND RITES\nIN ASHTABULA\nAttending the funeral services\nfor Arnold J. Smesik, 28, of Ash\ntabula recently\nwere\nMr. and\nMrs. Steve Toth of Courtland st.,\nand their daughter,\nMrs. Steve\nTokar of Seventh st. Mr. Smesik\nwas a relative of the local fami\nlly.\nThe young\nman\ndied at his\nwo krat the Ohio and Western\nPennsylvania Dock Co. when he\nfell into the Ashtabula river and\ndrowned.\nA sister of the deceased is Mrs.\nMichael Bodi of N. St. Clair st.,\nPainesville.\nSTORE ENTERED _\nThe door at the rear of Isaly\u2019s\nDairyt store\nforced\non\nopen,\nHigh st. was\napparently by a\ncrowbar or similar object some\ntime before store opening hours\neraly Sunday morning. The door\nwas damaged\naround the lock,\nbut nothing was found to be dis\nturbed and nothing was missed\nby the store manager.\nTheodore Olle\nConfined To Hospital\nThe condidtion\nof\nTheodore\nOlle of 680 N. St. Clair st., who\nwas removed to Lake County Me\nmorial hospital Sunday in a seri\nous condition, is much improved\ntoday it was learned.\nHe\nhad\nbeen seriously ill at his home for\ntwo days. It was finally discov\nered that he had a ruptured ap\npendix.\nMr. Olle operates Ted Olle's\nGarage at 711 Eagle st., Fair\nport.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe wish to thank the hostess\nes Mrs.\nWalter Lurvey,\nMrs.\nJohn Holson, Sr., and Mrs. Mau\nno Saari, those who participated\nin\nthe\nprogram,\nour\nmany\nfriends and relatives, and every\none for the lovely gifts and all\nwho helped to make the surprise\nparty in our honor the success\nthat it was.\nMr. and Mrs. Jack Mononen\nVILLAGE\nRESTAURANT\ny\n336 High Street\nFAIRPORT\nCATECHISM CLASSES\nAT ST. ANTHONY\u2019S\nRESUME IN SEPTEMBER\nA schedule of catechism class\nes at St. Anthony\u2019s was announc\ned today by Rev. Fr. Jutius Vig\nias, simultaneous with and ap\npropriate to the\nof the school\nannouncement\nopening.\nFather\nVigias advised that all St. An\nthony\u2019s pupils should attend the\nchildren\u2019s\nSundays.\nmass at 9\na.\nm. on\nCatechetical\ninstructions for\nhigh school studenst will be con\nducted the first and third Tues\nday and Thursday of each month.\nat 7 p. m. Instructions in cate-,\nchism for adults will be on Wed\nnesdays at 7 p. m. from Sept. 15\non.\nPicnic ommittee Lauded\nFather Vigias\nthis\nI\nweek ex\npressed his gratitude to George\nGedeon, his committee and co\nworkers for their excellent work\ndone in planning and arranging\nthe annual picnic held last Sun\nday, and voiced his appreciation\non the excellent cooperation of\nall who attended the event. The\npastor of St. Anthony\u2019s also ex\ntended his heartfelt thanks to\nFrank Stanton for granting per\nmission to the parish to use his\nfine picnic grounds.\nHe Named Montevideo\nMagellan, the famous Portuguese\nexplorer, is credited with\nmany\nthings, and one thing more to his\ncredit is the name of the city of\nMontevideo. In 1519, on his expedi\ntion up the Rio de la Plata, one of\nhis sailors cried out in Portuguese,\n\"Monte vide eu!\u201d which means, \u201cI\nhe\nsee a mountain.\" Little did\nknow that he was looking at the\nlater-day site of Montevideo, which\ntook as its own the name the\nPortuguese sailor had given to it.\nBetsy Ross, maker of the first\nAmerican flag, was an upholster\ner and carpet maker.\nTYPEWRITERS\nBuy at Today\u2019s Low Prices!\nSelect from Underwood, Remington or Corona.\nConvenient Time Payment Plan\nNEW\nUNDERWOOD\nCHAMPION\nPORTABLE\nThe Complete Portable that\nhas Every Wanted Feature.\n$89.57\n(plus tax)\nNEW\nUNDERWOOD STANDARD\nThe machine with rhythm touch and\nrhythm shift.\nUNDERWOOD\u2019S LATEST!\nCnderood\nwmnalei\nwil...\nNEW\nUNDERWOOD UNIVERSAL\nIncorporates Underwood features at\nan economical price.\nt\n$76.85\n(plus tax)\nNeal Printing Co.\n440 High Street\nPhone 5541\nFairport\nPASSING THE BUCK\nbv Bill Ware\nWant Floors, No Ceilings\nPerhaps it\u2019s my ignorance, but\nI am considerably confused over\na couple of matters having to\ndo with economics. I wisa my\nfarmer friends would hasten to\nset me right.\nAs I recall,\nfor\ninstance,\nit\nseems to me that many of those\nagricultural acquaintances were\npretty bitter over OPA and were\ntickled to death when Congress\nslew it. I\u2019m\nthey were\nnot\nsure whether\nagainst OPA chiefly\nbecause it allegedly curcumvent\ned the natural laws of free en\nterprise, but that may not have\nbeen it.\nAnyway, this morning\u2019s gazet\nte carried a news story which re\nminded me that, though the eco\nnomic ceiling is gone these two\nyears, we still have an economic\nfloor\nis.\nfor some things, that\nDried fruits, for instance. And\nwool and tobacco, not to speak\nof peanuts, wheat, potatoes and\ndried eggs. Congress has specifi\ncally directed the Department of\nAgriculture to build a price floor\nunder these commodities, even if\nit has to buy millions of dollars\nworth of the stuff with taxpay\ners\u2019 money, which it has done\nand is doing.\nWell now,\nwhat gives?\nWe\ndon\u2019t let prices fall, but we let\nthem soar as high as they want\nto go. If, let us say, the terrific\nwheat crop this year finally\nmeets the world\u2019s needs and then\nsome, and the price begins to\nslide\nfrom\nthe\nastonomical\nheights to which it has risen, in\nstead of lokoing forward to a\n15-cent loaf of bread again, the\ncustomer apparently will have to\nkick in a few more tax dollars\nto make sure the loaf stays at\n20 cents.\nThose figures mav be all wet,\nbut the principle is there. Appa\nrently we are going to let steel\nprices, and auto prices, and the\nprice of bananas slide when the\ninevitable\npression\u201d\n\"recession\"\nor\n\u201cde\nhits us. Also wages,\nand I suppost dividends and pro\nfits.\nBut the cost of wheat for our\nbread, and\nwool for our suits?\nOh no! They, my friends, are not\nheaded for the toboggan. There\nIs a 'floor\nthere\nwhich keeps\nthem from tumbling and getting\nhurt.\nMy affinity for the soil and\nmy sympathy for the farmer\u2019s\nviewpoint is well known. But I\nam pretty\nsure\nthat the \"city\nslicker\u201d got himself \"out-slick\nered\u201d in this deal with the fast\ntalking, heavy\nlobby.\nspending farm\n\nEducation Plays Tenth\nFiddle In Lobby Brigade\nIf there are some school teach\ners in the newly formed Lake\nCounty Young Republicans Club,\nthey are in an excellent position\nto inquire whether Gov. Dewey\u2019s\nreported antipathy toward their\nprofession is true or merely a\n(Continued on page 16)\nOPEN FRI.-SAT. TO 9 P.M.\nTOUBMAN'S\nCor. 4th and High\nFairport\nOne Stop Shopping\nFor Your Entire Family and Your Home\nI\n6/\nBAC70\n1 S.AOOL\n5\nSpecial Purchase!\nGirls\u2019 2.98 Cotton\nDRESSES\nFast Color\nSlub Poplins\nand Percales\nSizes 7 to 12\n199\nNOW! When you\u2019re preparing\nback to school wardrobes\nTOUBMAN\u2019S brings this sav\ning. Floral prints, stripes and\nsolids. Perky bows, lace and\nembroidery trims.\nTots\u2019 2.49 Cotton\nDRESSES\nPoplins and percales, prints\nand solids. Adorable\nstyles. 1 to 6 _\n1.39\n12.98 SNOW SUITS\nStyles for Boys and Girls. Sizes 1 to\n6, 1 and 2-piece suits with ZIPPER\nFRONT. Some with sheepskin fur col\nlars. Helmets and hats.\nWarmly interlined. _\n7.98\nGIRLS\u2019 29.98 DOUBLERS\n100% Reprocessed Wool Melton\nMatching Slack.\nA truly exceptional value, well styled\nand warmly interlined. Some leopard\nIne trim, also grey with green\nand grey with wine._\n16\u201d","height":"20744","width":"14352"}}
